<i>And there went up a mist from the earth. . .</i></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/unaginatakuroshio.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Naginata Kuroshio</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Conjurer</span><br>  Posts: 125<br> <font color=#333333>(10/9/01 5:36:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerthingstokill.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=308.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.rose-hulman.edu/~acuffnd/Reference/nagpic.gif height=118 width=95></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Partnering?</span><hr size=1> My everyday group is myself (56 mage), a 55 Paladin (well, he's 53 now, but he vows to be 55 by next week... and I believe him <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ), and a 53 Ranger.  We can take down just about anything that doesn't summon, easily.  There's alot of advantages to this kind of group:<br>
<br>
First, in normal fights, the ranger takes the aggro, and the Paladin heals him as necessary... Rangers can't heal, but Paladins sort of can, at least, enough to keep the ranger from getting annihilated.  It helps that the Ranger has good gear (And swiftwind).  Example of these kinds of fights - Rapid pulling of Othmir warriors/shamans in Cobalt Scar.  I know I can solo them, but I we can cut through them like nothing in this little group.<br>
<br>
In fights that are a bit tougher than that, the ranger tries to keep aggro on my pet, with jolt, but isn't afraid to tank a bit, while the Paladin stands back and stuns (Deepwater bracers are basically the same thing as a 60% or so slow), switching back and forth between bracer stuns and regular chain stuns, depending on how the fight is going.  Example is the zone in in (old) chardok.  In this fight and the &quot;easier&quot; fight, I'll nuke from time to time, depending on how things are going<br>
<br>
In fights that are tougher than that, the paladin does the same thing, as far as keeping the thing stunned as much as aggro permits, usually with the bracer, and the ranger will stand back and fire some arrows into the thing while the pet, and the damage shield, do most of the work.  When the pet gets kind of low, the ranger will root (Malosi is a must have, usually), and I'll summon a new pet.  These kind of tactics require much better teamwork, and aren't so good for experience... but we're going to try this on Undertow sometime soon.  I think we'll be able to pull it off, we've done far crazier <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
So, basically, the point here is that it's not som uch what's in your group, as how you use it.  There are some classes you can NOT partner with... Monks, some rogues (Depending on how well they play with pets), and warriors.  But, if you have a good person behind the character, mages compliment most other teams well, and are complimented well by smart, clever people playing most classes.  For instance, we once replaced the ranger in my group with a warrior... and chardok was still pretty easy for us.  Ingenuity is the key to playing a mage, especially the higher you get.  Try stuff that other people haven't, and be willing to die!  They said I was crazy when I told them I was going to solo to and kill Xalgoz at level 51.  And I died trying it.  But now when someone needs to kill him, they know who to call <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><table width="100%" border="0">
